  "summary": "A 2018 interfaith Freedom Seder organized around Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s critique of racism, materialism, and militarism, with sexism added as a fourth concern. It offers coherent cup rituals, environmental readings, shared-matzah practice, and a powerful communal close, but it is a historically situated activist work with extensive embedded speeches, songs, and quotations.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Prophetic, interfaith, movement-centered, lyrical, and participatory, combining source-authored ritual with civil-rights speeches, labor history, song, and ecological theology.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Social-justice and interfaith theme paths",
      "Labor dignity and shared-matzah rituals",
      "Environmentally focused cups, karpas, charoset, and Dayenu",
      "A peace-focused Nirtzah built around collective responsibility and the Beloved Community"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "Many readings assume knowledge of Dr. King's speeches, the labor movement, interfaith history, and 2018 U.S. politics.",
      "Descriptions of lynching, genocide, gun violence, militarism, poverty, and ecological disaster need content notes and a pass option.",
      "The source uses distinctive Breath-of-Life theology that should be introduced, not silently treated as universal Jewish wording.",
      "Most major sequences contain embedded works requiring author-level attribution and rights review."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "The source is forthrightly activist and reflects a 2018 U.S. political context. Use its universal commitments to love, labor dignity, justice, peace, and shared humanity, but label named policies, technologies, statistics, public officials, and campaign tactics as historical. Do not convert its political metaphors into unsourced current claims, and do not use its rhetoric to demean any people collectively.",
    "creditContext": "Credit Rabbi Arthur Waskow, The Shalom Center, and the MLK+50 Labor-Justice Interfaith Freedom Seder on the final sources page. Preserve every source-presented credit for Dr. King, Heschel, the Jewish Labor Committee, poets, translators, song traditions, and other contributors; the CC license applies only as stated by the source."
  },
